    # [Scene: Old Lighthouse | Night — Wind Raking the Stones]

    scene bg ch13_4001e7_23 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse piano, brittle as glass; distant thunder like an audience's slow clap]
    "You climb the lighthouse steps with Elias Park behind you. Each stair is a sentence of the day, worn smooth by other people's hands. You smell damp wool and the ash of a too-quick cigarette—Elias Park's attempt at a steadiness that fails."
    show elias_park at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_park "You could have run a calmer strategy."
    show mira_santos at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_santos "Calmer strategies didn't stop the clauses from being written. They just made the truth slower."

    elias_park "I am not ready to lose you to this."

    mira_santos "You're not going to lose me—' (you want to mean it; it fractures) '—unless we give up the right to be a town on our own terms."

    elias_park "And if the town comes at you? If legal injunctions and supervised closures come for the Saltworks and your name—if they make you a symbol to be discredited—what then?"
    "You feel the question probe a place you keep for quiet things. You think of Aunt Lila Santos's stories, of the coral scarf around your neck, of Harper Kline's frightened shadow leaving the plaza. There is"
    "an ache that is not only for the town but for the private softness you have with Elias Park—that small harbor you have not fully anchored in public."

    mira_santos "Then I will answer. I will tell the truth louder. I will not step aside so others can be written out."

    elias_park "And us?"

    mira_santos "We will be tested. Maybe we break. Maybe we go on. But right now the choice is whether I'm willing to sacrifice the town's memory for a quieter life with you. I can't."
    hide elias_park
    hide mira_santos

